<DOC><DOCNO> AP880604-0069 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0705EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Summit-Ministers 1stLd-Writethru a0523 06-04 0183</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Summit-Ministers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,0185</SECOND><HEAD>Ministers' Coalition Praise Summit, Seek Meeting On Apartheid</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Fixes 2nd-graf typo in Gorbachev's first name.</NOTE><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A coalition of clerics led by Southern ChristianLeadership Conference President Joseph Lowery praised the Moscowsummit meeting, but said they wanted to meet with President Reaganto discuss policies on South Africa.   The group watched the meeting this week between Reagan andSoviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, Lowery, an Atlanta minister, tolda news conference Friday.   ``We observed with appreciation the president's emphasis onhuman rights in the Soviet Union, with particular concern for theright of dissent and freedom of religion,'' Lowery said.   Lowery said the group wants to meet with Reagan, Vice PresidentGeorge Bush and Secretary of State George Shultz to ``assist thepresident in developing and shaping our nation's policies inopposing apartheid and calling for protection of human rights inSouth Africa.''   Apartheid is South Africa's system of racial segregation.   Joining Lowery were the Rev. Patricia McClurg of the NationalCouncil of Churches, Rabbi Alvin Sugarman of Reformed Judaism andseveral area ministers.</TEXT></DOC>